9,27.18,17.68,22.79,22.86,33.32,23.53,24.37,32.34,28.48,27.75,26.7,23.11,20.2,25.87,27.99,33.63,25.81,22.36,25.0,22.9,19.2,20.34,18.61,21.74,16.95,17.19,17.95,14.5,15.44,13.19,16.78,14.01,18.94,17.21,14.89,12.46,12.28,13.08,13.6,14.24,14.74,13.01,18.71,12.69,14.47,12.48,12.85,17.69,15.88,19.45,16.73,18.03,14.94,13.9,24.09,19.54,16.43,15.66,24.66,21.51,26.47,18.62,17.61,17.48,17.38,17.52,14.79,14.76,16.65,17.3,20.0,16.08,13.47,15.84,21.77,17.93,25.09,21.04,18.81,18.06,19.87,17.65,18.77]}},"releases":{"fomc":"Jul 29","ecb":"Jul 23","jobs":"Aug 7","ismMfg":"Aug 3","ismServices":"Aug 5","claims":"Weekly (Thu)","cpi":"Aug 12 (est.)","ppi":"Aug 13 (est.)","retail":"Aug 17 (est.)","housing":"Aug 17 (est.)","existing":"Aug 21 (est.)","pce":"Jul 28 (est.)","gdp":"Jul 28 (est.)","umich":"Aug 14 (est.)","chinaPMI":"Jul 31 (est.)","daily":"Daily","gdpnowKey":"Updates ~weekly"},"commentary":{"source":"claude","generated":"2026-07-21","items":[{"tag":"Energy","text":"WTI ($79.20) and Brent ($81.62) are well off their April 2026 peak \u2014 Brent averaged $85/b in June and the EIA now forecasts $74/b for Q3. The partial re-opening of the Strait of Hormuz following the June 18 US-Iran MOU is the proximate driver: global supply rebounded 4.1 mb/d in June, though output remains ~9.4 mb/d below pre-war levels. For energy-sector credits, the price relief eases near-term liquidity stress for E&P borrowers, but the forward curve implies continued margin compression; tanker attacks reported as recently as this week signal the ceasefire is fragile."},{"tag":"Labor","text":"June payrolls printed a deeply disappointing 57K (vs. 129K prior), the softest monthly print in years, yet initial claims just fell to 208K (from 217K) and AHE reaccelerated to +3.52% YoY. The divergence \u2014 weak headline job creation alongside firm wages and low claims \u2014 suggests compositional churn rather than a broad cyclical downturn, consistent with the FOMC's 'higher-for-longer' posture. For special situations investors, sectors reliant on low-cost labor (retail, logistics, food service credits) face ongoing margin pressure from wage inflation running above productivity gains."},{"tag":"Inflation","text":"The inflation picture is bifurcating: headline CPI has fallen sharply to 3.46% (from 4.17% prior) as energy prices deflate, but core PCE remains sticky at 3.41% and the June FOMC minutes flagged tariff pass-through, AI-driven demand, and energy input costs as the primary upward forces on core goods and services. PPI at 5.51% is still running well above CPI, indicating producer margins remain compressed and further downstream pass-through is possible. For credit investors, issuers with pricing power and fixed-cost structures are better positioned to maintain coverage; leveraged names in commodity-exposed industries face a cost-squeeze even as headline inflation cools."},{"tag":"Policy/Rates","text":"The Fed is on hold at 3.75% with the FOMC's modal path implying no cuts until Q2 2027 at the earliest, and CME FedWatch is now pricing meaningful odds of hikes in H2 2026. The 10Y UST has risen to 4.55% (+17bps from prior) and the 2s10s curve has steepened to +39bps, reflecting both sticky inflation and a term premium rebuild. This is a fundamentally adverse backdrop for HY refinancing: all-in coupons for new issuance remain punishing and the window for liability management exercises is narrow and volatile."},{"tag":"Credit Markets","text":"HY OAS widened modestly to 273bps (+6bps) and IG OAS to 79bps (+3bps) \u2014 spreads remain historically tight despite elevated rate volatility and decelerating growth, suggesting the market is not yet pricing a material deterioration in credit fundamentals. VIX at 18.77 (up from 17.65) indicates rising but not acute risk aversion. For special situations, tight index-level spreads mask dispersion at the single-name level; stressed/distressed opportunities are more likely to emerge in energy-adjacent, consumer discretionary, and rate-sensitive real estate credits where the macro headwinds are most acute."},{"tag":"Growth","text":"The Atlanta Fed GDPNow estimate for Q1 has improved to +1.68% (from +1.24%) but the last official GDP print was only +2.1% in Q4 2025, following a near-stall at +0.5%. ISM Services PMI held solidly at 54.0 in June (24th consecutive month in expansion), while manufacturing has been in expansion for six straight months at 53.3, providing a resilient demand backdrop. However, UMich consumer sentiment at 44.8 \u2014 near crisis lows \u2014 warns that the transmission from soft confidence into actual spending could accelerate if energy prices or mortgage costs re-spike."},{"tag":"Consumer/Housing","text":"June retail sales rose only +0.2% MoM (the softest in five months), though core control-group sales ex-gas, autos, and building materials rose a healthier +0.5%. Existing home sales fell 2.4% MoM to 4.09M SAAR, missing expectations, with median prices hitting an all-time high of $440,600 and the 30Y mortgage at 6.55% continuing to freeze out move-up buyers. Housing starts surged to 1,427K (from 1,199K), driven by builders targeting higher price-point units \u2014 a dynamic that underscores the 'K-shaped' housing market and limits the collateral support available to lower-credit-quality RMBS and construction lending exposures."}]},"extraSeries":{"ecb":{"value":"2.25%","delta":"Hiked 25bps at June 11 meeting \u2014 first hike since 2023 \u2014 from 2.00%; effective from June 17. Next decision July 23 (non-projection meeting).","dir":"up"},"chinaPMI":{"value":"50.3","delta":"NBS official PMI, June 2026 (released June 30). Up from 50.0 in May; beat 50.1 consensus. Third consecutive month in expansion, driven by AI-linked high-tech exports; domestic demand and employment remain soft.","dir":"up"},"ismServices":{"value":"54.0","delta":"June 2026 (released July 6), down 0.5pts from May's 54.5 but 24th straight month in expansion. Employment subindex returned to expansion at 51.2 for first time in four months.","dir":"down"},"retailSales":{"value":"+0.2% m/m","delta":"June 2026 advance estimate (Census Bureau, July 16). Smallest gain in five months; gasoline stations dragged (-5.3%). Ex-gas +0.7%; control group +0.5%. May revised up to +1.0%.","dir":"down"},"existingHome":{"value":"4.09M","delta":"June 2026 SAAR (NAR, released ~July 9), down 2.4% MoM from 4.19M in May; missed 4.20M consensus. Median price hit all-time high of $440,600. Inventory 4.6 months of supply.","dir":"down"}},"themes":{"refiWall":"The 2026-27 HY refinancing wall remains acute with the 10Y at 4.55% and all-in new-issue yields still punishing; the modest spread widening in HY (273bps) has not been enough to offset the rate-driven cost-of-capital increase, making liability management transactions expensive and selective. Issuers with near-term maturities in rate-sensitive or energy-exposed sectors face the highest refinancing risk, and any further hawkish Fed repricing (markets now pricing hike odds for H2 2026) would materially compress the execution window.","tariffs":"The Supreme Court's February 2026 ruling that IEEPA tariffs were unconstitutional removed the broadest tariff authority, but the administration replaced them with a 10% global Section 122 surcharge that expires July 24, 2026 \u2014 creating an imminent policy cliff with multiple possible outcomes (expiry, Congressional extension, or substitution via Section 301/232). The effective tariff rate stood at 7.2% as of May 2026 (vs. 2.3% in Jan 2025), with China facing 23.4%, and steel/aluminum at 41.2%; tariff-driven cost pass-through remains a live inflation risk embedded in core PCE and PPI.","mideast":"The June 18 US-Iran MOU to end hostilities and reopen the Strait of Hormuz provided material relief \u2014 Brent fell ~$22/b in June from May \u2014 but vessel attacks near the strait were reported as recently as this past week, underscoring that the ceasefire is fragile and the risk premium has not fully evaporated. The EIA forecasts Brent averaging $74/b in Q3 and $65/b in 2027 contingent on swift de-escalation, but world oil supply remains ~9.4 mb/d below pre-war levels, keeping energy-cost inflation and supply-chain disruption as tail risks that could rapidly re-price credit spreads in energy-intensive industries."}}